article:
'ISO 3166-1' is part of the ISO 3166 standard published by the International
Organization for Standardization (ISO), and defines codes for the names of
countries, dependent territories, and special areas of geographical interest.
The official name of the standard is Codes for the representation of names of
countries and their subdivisions – Part 1: Country codes. It defines three
sets of country codes:
* ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 â two-letter country codes which are the most widely used
  of the three, and used most prominently for the Internet's country code top-
  level domains (with a few exceptions).
* ISO 3166-1 alpha-3 â three-letter country codes which allow a better visual
  association between the codes and the country names than the alpha-2 codes.
* ISO 3166-1 numeric â three-digit country codes which are identical to those
  developed and maintained by the United Nations Statistics Division, with the
  advantage of script (writing system) independence, and hence useful for people
  or systems using non-Latin scripts.

The alphabetic country codes were first included in ISO 3166 in 1974, and the
numeric country codes were first included in 1981. The country codes have been
published as ISO 3166-1 since 1997, when ISO 3166 was expanded into three parts
to include codes for subdivisions and former countries.

As a widely used international standard, ISO 3166-1 is implemented in other
standards and used by international organizations, to allow
facilitation of the exchange of goods and information. However, it is
not the only standard for country codes. Other country codes used by many
international organizations are partly or totally incompatible with ISO 3166-
1, although some of them closely correspond to ISO 3166-1 codes.
